{"cursor":"18307","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n, the boundary between gas and liquid runs from the triple point to the\ncritical point. Freeze-drying (blue arrow) brings the system around the triple\npoint, avoiding the direct liquid-gas transition seen in ordinary drying time\n(green arrow).]]\n\n\n'Freeze-drying,' also known as 'lyophilisation,' 'lyophilization,' or\n'cryodesiccation,' is a dehydration process typically used to preserve a\nperishable material or make the material more convenient for transport. Freeze-\ndrying works by freezing the material and then reducing the surrounding pressure\nto allow the frozen water in the material to sublimate directly from the solid\nphase to the gas phase.\n","linknr":289,"url":"Freeze_drying","recorded":1362893059,"links":45,"instances":["food","unit","biology","blood","metallurgy","chemistry","unit"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Dried foods","Food preservation","Preservation methods","Unit operations","NASA spin-off technologies"],"headings":["The origins of freeze drying","The freeze-drying process","Properties of freeze-dried products","Freeze-drying protectants","Applications of freeze-drying","Freeze-drying equipment","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a6/Drying.svg/220px-Drying.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bc/Benchtop_freeze_dryer.JPG/220px-Benchtop_freeze_dryer.JPG","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/15/Freeze-Dried-Ice-Cream.jpg/220px-Freeze-Dried-Ice-Cream.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7b/Freeze_dried_bacon_bars_%28cropped%29.jpg/220px-Freeze_dried_b